Last week we ended by considering relationships between continuous variables. We used scatter plots.

In [11]:
sns.relplot(data = penguins, x='flipper_length_mm', y='bill_depth_mm', height=8)

plt.show()

Trend lines to show the linear relationship between the two variables.

In [12]:
sns.lmplot(data = penguins, x='flipper_length_mm', y='bill_depth_mm', height=8)

plt.show()

Group by a categorical variable to show the relationships change across groups.

In [13]:
sns.lmplot(data = penguins, x='flipper_length_mm', y = 'bill_depth_mm', hue='species', height=8)

plt.show()

Correlation coefficients¶

Calculate the correlation coefficient between two variables in the DataFrame.

In [15]:
penguins.loc[:, ['flipper_length_mm', 'bill_depth_mm']].corr()
Out[15]:
flipper_length_mm bill_depth_mm
flipper_length_mm 1.000000 -0.583851
bill_depth_mm -0.583851 1.000000

Visualize the correlation plot as a heat map.

In [16]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

sns.heatmap(data = penguins.loc[:, ['flipper_length_mm', 'bill_depth_mm']].corr(),
            ax=ax)

plt.show()
In [17]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

sns.heatmap(data = penguins.loc[:, ['flipper_length_mm', 'bill_depth_mm']].corr(),
            vmin=-1, vmax=1, center = 0,
            ax=ax)

plt.show()
In [18]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

sns.heatmap(data = penguins.loc[:, ['flipper_length_mm', 'bill_depth_mm']].corr(),
            vmin=-1, vmax=1, center = 0,
            cmap='coolwarm',

plt.show()

Lastly I like to annot if we don't have dozens and dozens of variables.

In [19]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

sns.heatmap(data = penguins.loc[:, ['flipper_length_mm', 'bill_depth_mm']].corr(),
            vmin=-1, vmax=1, center = 0,
            cmap='coolwarm',
            annot=True, annot_kws={'size': 20},
            ax=ax)

plt.show()

In [25]:
corr_per_species = penguins.loc[:, ['flipper_length_mm', 'bill_depth_mm', 'species']].groupby(['species']).corr()
In [28]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, len(the_species), figsize=(18,6), sharex=True, sharey=True)

for ix, x in enumerate(the_species):
    sns.heatmap(data = corr_per_species.loc[x],
                vmin=-1, vmax=1, center=0,
                cmap='coolwarm', cbar=False,
                annot=True, annot_kws={'size': 25},
                ax=axs[ix])
    
    axs[ix].set_title('Species: '+x)

plt.show()

2D Histograms¶

In [29]:
sns.relplot(data = penguins, x='flipper_length_mm', y='bill_depth_mm')

In [30]:
sns.relplot(data = penguins, x='flipper_length_mm', y='bill_depth_mm', s=250)

plt.show()

Change the transparency of the markers to help display density or concentration of the observations.

In [33]:
sns.relplot(data = penguins, x='flipper_length_mm', y='bill_depth_mm', alpha=0.33)

plt.show()

The 2D histogram is intended to show the density via counts. Discretizes the space and counts the number of observations per bin.

In [36]:
sns.displot(data = penguins, x='flipper_length_mm', y='bill_depth_mm', kind='hist')

plt.show()

Turn on the color bar legend to show the counts.

In [37]:
sns.displot(data = penguins, x='flipper_length_mm', y='bill_depth_mm', kind='hist', cbar=True)

plt.show()

We can easily facet by grouping variables with the figure level function.

In [38]:
sns.displot(data = penguins, x='flipper_length_mm', y='bill_depth_mm', col='species',
            kind='hist', cbar=True)

plt.show()

2D density plot smoothes out the histogram.

More control over the individual components is found within the sns.PairGrid().

In [76]:
g = sns.PairGrid(data = penguins)

g.map_upper(sns.histplot)
g.map_lower(sns.kdeplot)
g.map_diag(sns.histplot)

plt.show()
